BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/physics-seminar-with-michael-cervia"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Quantum Computing for Fundamental Physics\n\nQuantum informatio
 n science is an emerging field that offers new tools to help study quantum 
 systems. In particular\, quantum hardware can more naturally encode degrees
  of freedom from problems in quantum mechanics\, thereby enabling more scal
 able computations. This seminar will introduce universal quantum computatio
 n and discuss examples of problems in nuclear and particle physics that may
  be addressed more directly with the aid of quantum computing techniques\, 
 such as real-time simulations of gauge theory and neutrino interactions. Fu
 rther\, obstacles to quantum computing such as device noise and limited ava
 ilability of hardware will be outlined\, along with potential solutions.\n\
 nDr. Michael J. Cervia works as a Postdoctoral Scholar at the University of
  Washington\, Seattle. Michael earned bachelor’s degrees in mathematics and
  physics from The University of Chicago (2016) and a doctorate from Univers
 ity of Wisconsin-Madison (2021)\, writing a thesis on neutrino interactions
  and quantum many-body theory while working with Baha Balantekin. They are 
 interested how the study of quantum field theories could be aided with the 
 use of quantum computers as well as how field theories may be reformulated 
 to better “fit” on quantum devices. More generally\, Michael’s research inv
 olves studies of entanglement and quantum corrections to mean-field calcula
 tions in nuclear and particle physics problems.
DTEND:20260312T003000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260311T233000Z
GEO:45.480964;-122.630146
