BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lewis Clark": "https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/371962-balancing-life-and-leadership-courage-to-lead-in-chal"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lewis_clark
X-SOURCE:Lewis Clark
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260313
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260314
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of Education and Counseling
SUMMARY:Balancing Life and Leadership: Courage to Lead in Challenging Tim
 es (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:Early spring a time of paradox. A season of balancing light a
 nd dark\, rest and activity\, tending to new sprouts\, and shedding what 
 no longer serves us.&#160\;This liminal space between the dormancy of win
 ter and the blossoming of spring offers opportunity to tend to the equili
 brium of our lives and our leadership.Are you seeking to find balance in 
 your life\, and make changes to better serve who you want to be in the wo
 rld and how you want to show up?  We invite you to join us in this opport
 unity to pause and disconnect from the fast pace and distractions of dail
 y life\, and join other change-makers who dare to engage in their work wi
 th presence and compassion.This Courage to Lead® retreat provides the ti
 me and space for deep reflection\, renewal\, and the opportunity to:     
  Engage in self reflection\, invitational large and small group sharing\,
  artistic expression\, and other contemplative practices designed to supp
 ort access to inner wisdom          Build a trustworthy space for accessi
 ng and speaking our truths\, and listening to the truths of others       
    Explore our inner sources of leadership    Develop skills for holding 
 meaningful conversations and building relational trust        Learn pract
 ices for holding the complexities we encounter in our personal and profes
 sional communities      This retreat is open to people from diverse field
 s and is designed to help participants renew their passion and enthusiasm
  and commitment toward their leadership and community. Past participants 
 have included school-based educators and administrators\, activists\, wri
 ters\, clergy\, coaches\, doulas\, mental health practitioners\, and lead
 ers from nonprofit and corporate sectors. Leadership can also be reflecte
 d in the ways that we show up in the world through our professional\, fam
 ily\, or community life.    Stay centered.    It is your greatest gift   
  to the world\,    to those    you care about\,    to your own soul\,    
 in fact.      Whatever is required    for you to stay completely    cente
 red in your gifts–    to listen    to the silence    of the greater uni
 verse—    do that thing now\,    this very moment.      from Judy Brown
 \, November 3\, 2006\, The Art &amp\; Spirit of LeadershipDetails &amp\; 
 RegistrationRegistration for this retreat is now closedDates and Times: F
 riday-Sunday\, March 13-15\, 2026&#160\;Friday: 9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.Saturday:
  9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.Sunday: 9:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m.Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark
  Graduate School\, 615 S. Palatine Hill Road\, Portland\, ORFacilitators:
  Kevin Bacon\; Dawn Montgomery\, EdD\; Matsya SiosalRegistration: $425. I
 ncludes 16 PDUs or CEUs\, materials and supplies\, and Friday and Saturda
 y lunch\, beverages\, and snacks.&#160\;Lodging: Please note that this is
  not a residential retreat. The Lakeshore Inn (https://www.thelakeshorein
 n.com/) is the closest lodging option to campus\, and other options with 
 rates for L&amp\;C visitors can be found here (https://www.lclark.edu/vis
 it/places_to_stay/).Accessibility: We are committed to making our events 
 accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, please let us k
 now your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu with 
 questions.Scholarship Fund: We strive to keep our Courage retreats access
 ible to all who wish to participate. Please consider making a tax-deducti
 ble donation (https://engage.lclark.edu/register/gsecgiving?sys:gift:fund
 =4dfb9f4e-7351-4d84-91fe-531631c248c7&amp\;sys:gift:notes=Courage%20and%2
 0Renewal%20Retreats%20Scholarship%20Fund) to our scholarship fund.About t
 he Facilitators Kevin Bacon is a seasoned educator who has dedicated his 
 career to student outcomes&#160\;and community engagement. He is a retire
 d Portland Public Schools administrator that taught and administrated at 
 all three levels\, elementary\, middle and high.  In retirement\, he cont
 inues to support schools by substituting for principals and consulting as
  needed. He recently completed a three year term as the president of the 
 nonprofit\, Oregon Alliance of Black School Educators and served two year
 s on the board of the nonprofit Reading Results. He is proud of his accum
 ulative 38 years of service to nearly every student demographic in most s
 ectors of Portland. He has been a teacher\, student management specialist
 \, biotech education coordinator\, coach\, vice principal\, and principal
 .  Kevin received his Courage to Lead training and certification from the
  Center for Courage &amp\; Renewal in 2011. He has facilitated numerous r
 etreats since that time and brings energy\, insight\, and humility to eve
 ry gathering. Kevin has two adult children and loves spending his leisure
  time golfing\, traveling\, hiking and cycling. Dawn Montgomery\, EdD is 
 a change facilitator and insightful thought partner. She supports leaders
  from a wide variety of fields\, including educators\, nonprofit executiv
 es\, and community administrators as they find their way in challenging t
 imes. Assisting humans in their discovery and reconnection to their deepe
 st longings has been a passion for many years. Her commitment to environm
 ental and human health and healing resonates throughout her coaching prac
 tice and team facilitation. She believes transformation is born when a ci
 rcle of humans sit together to listen\, to speak their deepest truths and
  to share their wildest imaginations for change. She is expert at holding
  space for both individual leaders and teams as an executive coach\, conf
 lict mediator\, equity-focused professional developer and a certified Cou
 rage &amp\; Renewal facilitator. She is committed to making a difference 
 in the lives of individuals and their communities. Matsya Siosal has deve
 loped her skills in leadership and facilitation for over 25 years\, inclu
 ding roles with small and large for-profit corporations\, mission-driven 
 consumer goods companies\, higher education\, and as a consultant and ent
 repreneur. She has served as the director of the Center for Community Eng
 agement at Lewis &amp\; Clark since 2015\, after joining the department i
 n 2010 to work in marketing and program management. Matsya is also co-fou
 nder and managing partner of Sea-O-Salt Bath Company (http://www.seaosalt
 .com/). Matsya is an experienced certified facilitator of Courage &amp\; 
 Renewal programs. She has facilitated Circle of Trust\, Courage to Lead\,
  and Leading Together workshops and retreats since 2019\, and is trained 
 as a SoulCollage® (https://soulcollage.com/) facilitator. As a facilitat
 or and coach\, Matsya supports mission-driven leaders in accessing their 
 authentic voice\, and finding clarity and self-trust so they can show up 
 with wholeheartedness and sustainability in their lives and work.New work
 shops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest o
 n professional development related to your specific interests\, sign up f
 or our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Early spring
  a time of paradox. A season of balancing light and dark\, rest and activ
 ity\, tending to new sprouts\, and shedding what no longer serves us.&#16
 0\;This liminal space between the dormancy of winter and the blossoming o
 f spring offers opportunity to tend to the equilibrium of our lives and o
 ur leadership.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Are you seeking t
 o find balance in your life\, and make changes to better serve who you wa
 nt to be in the world and how you want to show up?</strong></p><p style="
 line-height: 1.5\;">  We invite you to join us in this opportunity to pau
 se and disconnect from the fast pace and distractions of daily life\, and
  join other change-makers who dare to engage in their work with presence 
 and compassion.</p><h4 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>This Courage to
  Lead® retreat provides the time and space for deep reflection\, renewal
 \, and the opportunity to:</strong></h4><ul><li><p style="line-height: 1.
 5\;">      Engage in self reflection\, invitational large and small group
  sharing\, artistic expression\, and other contemplative practices design
 ed to support access to inner wisdom    </p></li><li><p style="line-heigh
 t: 1.5\;">      Build a trustworthy space for accessing and speaking our 
 truths\, and listening to the truths of others    </p></li><li><p style="
 line-height: 1.5\;">      Explore our inner sources of leadership    </p>
 </li><li>Develop skills for holding meaningful conversations and building
  relational trust  </li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Learn pra
 ctices for holding the complexities we encounter in our personal and prof
 essional communities    </p></li></ul><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Thi
 s retreat is open to people from diverse fields and is designed to help p
 articipants renew their passion and enthusiasm and commitment toward thei
 r leadership and community. Past participants have included school-based 
 educators and administrators\, activists\, writers\, clergy\, coaches\, d
 oulas\, mental health practitioners\, and leaders from nonprofit and corp
 orate sectors. Leadership can also be reflected in the ways that we show 
 up in the world through our professional\, family\, or community life.</p
 ><blockquote><p style="font-size: 2.2rem\;">    Stay centered.<br />    I
 t is your greatest gift<br />    to the world\,<br />    to those<br />  
   you care about\,<br />    to your own soul\,<br />    in fact.  </p><p 
 style="font-size: 2.2rem\;">    Whatever is required<br />    for you to 
 stay completely<br />    centered in your gifts–<br />    to listen<br 
 />    to the silence<br />    of the greater universe—<br />    do that
  thing now\,<br />    this very moment.  </p><p class="quote-author">    
 from <em>Judy Brown\, November 3\, 2006\, The Art &amp\; Spirit of Leader
 ship</em></p></blockquote><hr /><h2><strong>Details &amp\; Registration</
 strong></h2><h5 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Registration for this 
 retreat is now closed</strong></h5><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>
 Dates and Times:</strong> Friday-Sunday\, March 13-15\, 2026&#160\;</p><p
  style="line-height: 1.5\; padding-left: 40px\;"><strong>Friday:</strong>
  9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.<br /><strong>Saturday:</strong> 9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.<br /><
 strong>Sunday:</strong> 9:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m.</p><p style="line-height: 1.
 5\;"><strong>Location:</strong> Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, 615 
 S. Palatine Hill Road\, Portland\, OR</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><s
 trong>Facilitators:</strong> Kevin Bacon\; Dawn Montgomery\, EdD\; Matsya
  Siosal</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Registration:</strong> $
 425. Includes 16 PDUs or CEUs\, materials and supplies\, and Friday and S
 aturday lunch\, beverages\, and snacks.&#160\;</p><p style="line-height: 
 1.5\;"><strong>Lodging:</strong> Please note that this <span style="text-
 decoration: underline\;"><strong>is not</strong></span> a residential ret
 reat. <a href="https://www.thelakeshoreinn.com/">The Lakeshore Inn</a> is
  the closest lodging option to campus\, and other options with rates for 
 L&amp\;C visitors can be <a href="https://www.lclark.edu/visit/places_to_
 stay/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">found here</a>.</p><p class="p1" st
 yle="font-size: 14px\; line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Accessibility:</strong
 > We are committed to making our events accessible to all needs and abili
 ties. When registering\, please let us know your access needs. Contact us
  at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu with questions<span style="font-weight
 : 400\;">.</span></p><p class="p1" style="font-size: 14px\; line-height: 
 1.5\;"><strong>Scholarship Fund:</strong> We strive to keep our Courage r
 etreats accessible to all who wish to participate. Please consider making
  a <a href="https://engage.lclark.edu/register/gsecgiving?sys:gift:fund=4
 dfb9f4e-7351-4d84-91fe-531631c248c7&amp\;sys:gift:notes=Courage%20and%20R
 enewal%20Retreats%20Scholarship%20Fund">tax-deductible donation</a> to ou
 r scholarship fund.</p><hr /><h2 style="line-height: 1.6\;"><strong>About
  the Facilitators</strong></h2><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong><pic
