SUMMARY:Applied Suicide Intervention Skills Training (ASIST) [In-Person]
DESCRIPTION:The Applied Suicide Intervention Skills Training (ASIST) is a
 n intensive\, interactive and practice-dominated course for those who wan
 t to feel more comfortable\, confident and competent in providing an inte
 rvention with someone who is having thoughts of suicide.&#160\;This works
 hop will provide extensive opportunities for supported skills practice an
 d shared participant experiences that enrich learning.After this workshop
 \, participants will have an increased ability to:      Recognize when so
 meone may be thinking about suicide          Provide a skilled interventi
 on\, including connect the person to further support          Guide the d
 evelopment of a safety plan through a collaborative\, helping relationshi
 p          Consider how personal and community attitudes about suicide af
 fect someone's openness to seek help and the caregiver's ability to provi
 de it          Reduce suicide stigma and build confidence and capacity to
  provide suicide first aidWho should attend? The training is for anyone i
 n a position of trust\, including mental health and addictions profession
 als\, school psychologists\, school counselors\, educators\, healthcare w
 orkers\, peer support and recovery specialists\, housing specialists\, la
 w enforcement\, faith leaders\, and community volunteers.  "Prior to part
 icipating in ASIST\, I was reluctant to get involved in conversations inv
 olving suicide because I felt uneasy about how to engage effectively. I w
 alked away from this training with clear and applicable tools to enter a 
 conversation with confidence and fearlessness\, equipped to support and c
 onverse openly about suicide. It was absolutely one of the most valuable 
 trainings I have experienced in my career."  - Counselor\, Roosevelt High
  SchoolTraining credits are NASP and NASW-approved for Continuing Profess
 ional Development (CPD).Details &amp\; RegistrationRegistration for this 
 course is closed.Dates and Time: Friday &amp\; Saturday\, March 13-14\, 2
 026\, 8:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.&#160\;Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate Sch
 ool\, South ChapelInstructors: Leslie Rodgers\, and Kathy Wilson-FeyCost 
 and Credits: $325\, includes 15 NASP-Approved CEUs or PDUs (12.75 NASW Cr
 edits). Alumni\, Adjuncts\, and GSEC Clinical Mental Health Supervisors s
 ave 20%.&#160\;Accessibility: We are committed to making our events acces
 sible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, please let us know y
 our access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cc
 e@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\;Stude
 nt Rate&#x2019\; registrations are for current students only and do not i
 nclude continuing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorsLeslie 
 Rodgers is a licensed clinical social worker and registered ASIST (Applie
 d Suicide Intervention Skills) trainer with over 20 years experience work
 ing with children and adults in various therapeutic settings\, including 
 group homes\, psychiatric hospitals\, and schools. Her current work has i
 nvolved implementing best practice procedures and providing staff develop
 ment in student threat assessment\, suicide prevention\, and crisis respo
 nse for school districts. She holds a BA from the University of Texas and
  a Masters in Social Work from Portland State University.Kathy Wilson-Fey
  is a registered ASIST Trainer and has clinical therapy and teaching expe
 rience in a variety of settings\, including community college\, community
  mental health\, and an international university. She has 15 years of exp
 erience as a mental health specialist in public schools\, where she worke
 d with students and families\, trained school staff on suicide interventi
 on\, and coordinated school support during crises. Kathy is fluent in Spa
 nish and is committed to equity work and cultural competence. She holds a
  BA from Whitman College and a Masters in Counseling Psychology from the 
 University of Oregon.New workshops and trainings are added to our calenda
 r regularly. For the latest on professional development related to your s
 pecific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaform
 s.net/4735441)
