X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lewis Clark": "https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/380696-of-humans-whales-and-goddesses-rethinking-ritual"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lewis_clark
X-SOURCE:Lewis Clark
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260317T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260317T170000
LOCATION:Miller Hall105
GEO:45.450858;-122.668265
SUMMARY:Of Humans\, Whales\, and Goddesses: Rethinking Ritual Action in T
 imes of Environmental Precarity\, Aike P. Rots (University of Oslo)
UID:20260317T230000Z-380696@www.lclark.edu
DTSTAMP:20260121T091216Z
URL:https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/380696-of-humans-whales
 -and-goddesses-rethinking-ritual
CATEGORIES:Open to the Public
LAST-MODIFIED:20260224T154439Z
ATTACH:https://www.lclark.edu/live/image/gid/82/width/80/height/80/crop/1
 /src_region/0,44,1200,1244/111529_aike-peter-rots-300-01.rev.1769015244.j
 pg
X-LIVEWHALE-TYPE:events
X-LIVEWHALE-ID:380696
X-LIVEWHALE-TIMEZONE:America/Los_Angeles
X-LIVEWHALE-IMAGE:https://www.lclark.edu/live/image/gid/82/width/80/heigh
 t/80/crop/1/src_region/0\,44\,1200\,1244/111529_aike-peter-rots-300-01.re
 v.1769015244.jpg
X-LIVEWHALE-IMAGE-CAPTION:Aike Peter Rots
X-LIVEWHALE-SUMMARY:<p>\n  What are rituals? Why do so many people engage
  in them? How do rituals shape culture\, religion\, and society? These ar
 e some of the foundational questions of anthropology and religious studie
 s\, discussed by generations of scholars. Many theories of ritual focus o
 n their social and political functions\, explaining how rituals serve to 
 make communities such as kinship groups or nation-states. Some classical 
 theories have also addressed the question of how rituals help humans esta
 blish and mediate relationships with powerful nonhuman actors such as ani
 mals\, climate phenomena\, rivers\, and spirits. These last theories take
  on new significance today\, in this time of polycrisis often referred to
  as the Anthropocene. What happens to ritual traditions when confronted w
 ith displacement\, the loss of livelihoods and companion species\, and th
 e destruction or pollution of places deemed sacred or ensouled? How do we
  preserve more-than-human relations in a time when so many relations are 
 severed? Do rituals still matter\, and if so\, how? These are some of the
  questions that I explore in my research.\n</p>\n<p>\n  This lecture disc
 usses some of the ways in which humans relate to the natural environment 
 through ritual action. I will use examples drawn from my fieldwork in Vie
 tnam and Japan\, conducted as part of the ERC-funded project <i>Whales of
  Power </i>(2019-2025)\, which studied human-animal relations in Asian po
 pular religion. I will also introduce my new ERC project\, <i>Maritime Go
 ddesses: Transnational Connections\, Blue Environments\, and Ritual Care 
 in East- and Southeast Asia </i>(2026-2031)\, which aims to develop a new
  theory of ritual action in the Anthropocene.\n</p>\n<p>\n  <strong>Bio:<
 /strong>\n</p>\n<p>\n  Aike P. Rots is Professor of East Asian Religions 
 at the University of Oslo. He has published widely on religion\, heritage
 \, and environmental issues in Japan\, Vietnam\, and elsewhere. He is the
  author of <i>Shinto\, Nature and Ideology in Contemporary Japan: Making 
 Sacred Forests</i> (Bloomsbury 2017) and co-author of the forthcoming <i>
 Animating Action: Changing the World with Anime\, Rituals\, and Robots</i
 > (with Yulia Frumer and Jolyon Thomas\, University of Hawai'i Press 2026
 ). He is also the co-editor of several special issues and books\, includi
 ng <i>Sacred Heritage in Japan</i> (Routledge 2020) and <i>Water Powers: 
 Sacred Aquatic Animals of the Asia-Pacific</i> (University of Hawai'i Pre
 ss 2026). He is currently writing a monograph on whale rituals in Vietnam
  and Japan\, while preparing his new ERC-funded project on goddess worshi
 p in East and Southeast Asia.<br />\n  <br />\n  <br />\n  Co-Sponsered w
 ith Asian Studies\n</p>
X-LIVEWHALE-TAGS:Environmental Studies Major|Environmental Studies Minor|
 open to the public|Religious Studies Major|Religious Studies Minor|send-t
 o-undergraduate|Sociology and Anthropology Major
END:VEVENT
