BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/pathogens-pests-and-policy-environmental-control-at-the-us-mexico-border"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Pathogens\, Pests\, and Policy: Environmental Control at the U.
 S.–Mexico Border\n\nMary E. Mendoza\, Assistant Professor of History and La
 tino/a Studies\, Penn State University \n\nWhen we think of the border toda
 y\, we often think of walls\, fences\, patrols\, and controlling the influx
  of undocumented immigrants. But the border has not always functioned to co
 ntrol human migration. In this talk\, Mary E. Mendoza will explain the caus
 es\, development\, and legacy of fence construction along the US-Mexico Div
 ide\, arguing that the border began as a project to control dynamic\, nonhu
 man nature\, and over time\, transformed into a project to change the natur
 e of human migration. As this process unfolded\, the construction of the bo
 rder and the construction of racial categories developed in tandem\, and th
 e environment played a critical role in this process.
DTEND:20260318T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260318T000000Z
GEO:45.480644;-122.627381
LOCATION:Psychology\, 105
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Pathogens\, Pests\, and Policy: Environmental Control at the U.S.-M
 exico Border
