BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/copy-of-community-dance-at-reed"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Performing Arts,Community
DESCRIPTION:Community Dance at Reed is a project that aims to bring togethe
 r members of the Reed College and broader Portland communities. We practice
  community dance as a mode of dancemaking and social intervention based on 
 the principles of collective creation. Weekly creative movement sessions—of
 fered one semester each academic year—are free and open to the public. No p
 revious dance experience necessary. These sessions offer a forum for dancin
 g and talking about social\, cultural\, and identity based issues. We welco
 me all bodies\, with a critical awareness of how race\, class\, ability\, g
 ender\, and sexuality impact the ways we relate to ourselves and one anothe
 r in public. Together\, we collaboratively create dance works and perform i
 n the dance department’s biannual concerts.\n\nFree and open to the public.
  No previous dance experience necessary. No registration required.
DTEND:20260320T023000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260320T011000Z
GEO:45.480983;-122.634105
LOCATION:Performing Arts Building\, 240 (Dance Studio)
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Community Dance at Reed
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52135856772409
URL:https://events.reed.edu/event/copy-of-community-dance-at-reed
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/because-of-you-screening"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Student,Social,Community
DESCRIPTION:Reed's Comparative Race and Ethnicity Studies program and the T
 heatre and Music Departments present a screening of "Because of You: A Hist
 ory of Kilawin Kolektibo" (Dahil Sa ‘Yo: Ang Storya Ng Kilawin Kolektibo) o
 n Thursday\, March 19\, 2026 at 6:30pm. To be followed by a Q&A with direct
 or Barbara Malaran\, and a reception.\n\nDirections: Navigate to "Reed Coll
 ege West Parking" to park at the lot adjacent to the Performing Arts Buildi
 ng. The entrance to the lot is across the street from the Crystal Springs R
 hododendron Garden. Room 320 is on the third floor which is accessible by s
 tairs or ramp/elevator.\n\nAbout "Because of You: A History of Kilawin Kole
 ktibo"\nDahil Sa ‘Yo: Ang Storya Ng Kilawin Kolektibo\n\nThis archival docu
 mentary traces the history of Kilawin Kolektibo\, a pioneering collective o
 f Filipinas who came together in NYC in the mid-nineties. Having experience
 d marginalization in Filipino culture because of their queerness and in mai
 nstream gay culture because of their race\, language\, and gender\, the mem
 bers of the group sought political empowerment and increased visibility.\n\
 nAbove all\, they sought to create a space of friendship and safety for tho
 se who found themselves suspended between cultures and identities. Kilawin 
 Kolektibo allowed them to transform their experience of oppression into one
  of joy and growth. Kilawin made lasting connections with similar groups in
  the global Filipino diaspora\, most significantly\, with Babaylan\, a quee
 r Filipinx group based in Toronto.\n\nCulling from a treasure trove of over
  a quarter-century’s worth of historic documentation\, including footage\, 
 photographs\, interviews\, and ephemera\, the film tells the inspiring stor
 y of members as they found each other\, fell in love\, and became each othe
 r’s lifeblood amidst a society that rejected them. From marching\, partying
 \, and protesting\, to its oftentimes incestuous sexual politics\, the film
  serves as an exhilarating memorial to the rebellion and nostalgia of the n
 ineties.
DTEND:20260320T033000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260320T013000Z
GEO:45.480983;-122.634105
LOCATION:Performing Arts Building\, 320
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Because of You/Dahil sa ‘yo: Film Screening and Director Q&A
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51783863266621
URL:https://events.reed.edu/event/because-of-you-screening
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/visiting-writers-series-natalie-shapero"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Natalie Shapero’s latest book is Stay Dead (2025)\, published i
 n the U.S. by Copper Canyon Press and in the U.K. by Out-Spoken Press. Her 
 writing has appeared in The New Yorker\, The London Review of Books\, The N
 ew York Review of Books\, The Paris Review\, The Nation\, and elsewhere. Sh
 e is the author of the previous poetry collections Popular Longing (2021)\,
  Hard Child (2017)\, and No Object (2013)\, and she has performed at The Pu
 litzer Arts Foundation\, The Poetry Project at St. Mark’s\, and elsewhere. 
 She lives in Los Angeles and teaches writing at UC Irvine. \n\nFee and open
  to the public.
