X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lewis Clark": "https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/381636-4-at-5-lecture-series-featuring-pamplin-professor-eme"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lewis_clark
X-SOURCE:Lewis Clark
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260408T180000
LOCATION:Miller Hall\, Room 105 (Lindner Auditorium)
GEO:45.450858;-122.668265
SUMMARY:4 at 5 Lecture Series Featuring Pamplin Professor Emeritus Stephe
 n Dow Beckham – Alaska Sojourners
DESCRIPTION:Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Lives in the Last Frontier  In-
 person at L&amp\;CLindner Auditorium\, Miller Center for Humanities (Mill
 er 105)Livestream hosted by the L&amp\;C Alaska Alumni Chapter  Livestrea
 m link shared upon registration  Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026  5:00 - 6:00 
 P.M.Click to Register (https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-93
 d8-4b90-b942-106ba20ba031)Times for those joining remotely from other tim
 e zones:8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ● 7 - 8 P.M Central ● 6 - 7 P.M. Mountain 
  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ● 2 - 3 P.M. Hawaii  This lecture series takes place
  the second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.About the lecture:  .
 Join this illuminating exploration of "Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Live
 s in the Last Frontier." Through vivid biographical vignettes\, Professor
 . Beckham brings to life a cast of extraordinary Americans drawn to the A
 laska Territory following its purchase in 1867.  From naturalist John Mui
 r to the flamboyant "Klondike Kate" Rockwell—who spent her final days i
 n Sweet Home\, Oregon—these figures embody the spirit\, ambition\, and 
 artistry of a transformative era. Discover the stories of Alexander Panta
 ges\, the visionary theater impresario\; Rockwell Kent\, the artist and a
 uthor who found inspiration in Alaska's wild beauty\; Robert Service\, th
 e famed "Bard of the Yukon"\; and Jack London\, the rebellious writer who
 se adventures fueled his iconic fiction. The lecture also features Sydney
  Laurence\, a pioneering Alaskan painter\, and Nils P. Adamson\, a dedica
 ted lighthouse keeper near Skagway\, who\, along with his son\, tended th
 e harbor lights at Coos Bay for more than six decades.About the presenter
 :Stephen Dow Beckham is Pamplin Professor Emeritus of History at Lewis &a
 mp\; Clark College\, where he served for forty-two years. A preeminent au
 thority on the American West and the Lewis &amp\; Clark Expedition\, Prof
 essor Beckham dedicated the majority of his career to teaching undergradu
 ate students in the College of Arts and Sciences\, while also contributin
 g his expertise to the Law School's Indian Law Program.  Renowned for his
  immersive teaching\, he famously led field-based courses retracing the L
 ewis &amp\; Clark trail on horseback and sailing the Northwest Coast. Bey
 ond the classroom\, he has served as an expert witness in over forty trib
 al rights cases and currently chairs the Oregon Committee on Historic Pre
 servation. A former Oregon Professor of the Year and recipient of the Ame
 rican Historical Association's Asher Distinguished Teaching Award\, Profe
 ssor Beckham also serves on the board of the Theodore Roosevelt President
 ial Library\, continuing his lifelong commitment to historical scholarshi
 p and conservation.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Alas
 ka Sojourners: Remarkable Lives in the Last Frontier<br /><br />  In-pers
 on at L&amp\;C<br /></strong>Lindner Auditorium\, Miller Center for Human
 ities (Miller 105)</p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Livestream 
 hosted by the L&amp\;C Alaska Alumni Chapter</strong><br />  Livestream l
 ink shared upon registration<strong><br /></strong></p><p style="text-ali
 gn: center\;">  Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026<br />  5:00 - 6:00 P.M.</p><p 
 style="text-align: center\;"><strong><a class="btn-small-style-1 btn-smal
 l-style-1" href="https://engage.lclark.edu/register/?id=c195d64c-93d8-4b9
 0-b942-106ba20ba031" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Click to Register</a>
 </strong></p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Times for those join
 ing remotely from other time zones:<br /></strong>8 - 9 P.M. Eastern ● 
 7 - 8 P.M Central ● 6 - 7 P.M. Mountain<br />  4 - 5 P.M. Alaska ● 2 
 - 3 P.M. Hawaii</p><p style="text-align: left\;">  This lecture series ta
 kes place the second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.</p><p style
 ="text-align: left\;"><strong>About the lecture:</strong></p><p data-path
 -to-node="3">  .Join this illuminating exploration of <strong data-path-t
 o-node="3" data-index-in-node="80">"Alaska Sojourners: Remarkable Lives i
 n the Last Frontier."</strong> Through vivid biographical vignettes\, Pro
 fessor. Beckham brings to life a cast of extraordinary Americans drawn to
  the Alaska Territory following its purchase in 1867.</p><p data-path-to-
 node="4">  From naturalist John Muir to the flamboyant "Klondike Kate" Ro
 ckwell—who spent her final days in Sweet Home\, Oregon—these figures 
 embody the spirit\, ambition\, and artistry of a transformative era. Disc
 over the stories of Alexander Pantages\, the visionary theater impresario
 \; Rockwell Kent\, the artist and author who found inspiration in Alaska'
 s wild beauty\; Robert Service\, the famed "Bard of the Yukon"\; and Jack
  London\, the rebellious writer whose adventures fueled his iconic fictio
 n. The lecture also features Sydney Laurence\, a pioneering Alaskan paint
 er\, and Nils P. Adamson\, a dedicated lighthouse keeper near Skagway\, w
 ho\, along with his son\, tended the harbor lights at Coos Bay for more t
 han six decades.</p><p><strong>About the presenter:</strong></p><p data-p
 ath-to-node="1"><strong data-path-to-node="1" data-index-in-node="0">Step
 hen Dow Beckham</strong> is Pamplin Professor Emeritus of History at Lewi
 s &amp\; Clark College\, where he served for forty-two years. A preeminen
 t authority on the American West and the Lewis &amp\; Clark Expedition\, 
 Professor Beckham dedicated the majority of his career to teaching underg
 raduate students in the College of Arts and Sciences\, while also contrib
 uting his expertise to the Law School's Indian Law Program.</p><p data-pa
 th-to-node="2">  Renowned for his immersive teaching\, he famously led fi
 eld-based courses retracing the Lewis &amp\; Clark trail on horseback and
  sailing the Northwest Coast. Beyond the classroom\, he has served as an 
 expert witness in over forty tribal rights cases and currently chairs the
  Oregon Committee on Historic Preservation. A former Oregon Professor of 
 the Year and recipient of the American Historical Association's Asher Dis
 tinguished Teaching Award\, Professor Beckham also serves on the board of
  the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library\, continuing his lifelong co
 mmitment to historical scholarship and conservation.</p>
