BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/postimperial-longing-cornelia-sorabji-in-victorian-oxford"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:A figure of both curiosity and celebrity during her life\, Corn
 elia Sorabji (1866-1954) has been recuperated as a feminist icon in both po
 stimperial academic scholarship and popular culture. This talk reconsiders 
 her time at Oxford in the late 19th century\, where she trained as a “lady 
 barrister\,” exploring what a complex figure she was and is – and tracking 
 how she has been transformed over the last thirty years into an object of p
 ostimperial desire\, if not nostalgia as well. \n\nAntoinette Burton is pro
 fessor of History and Swanlund Endowed Chair at the University of Illinois\
 , Urbana-Champaign. A historian of the modern British empire\, her work has
  used feminist and anti-colonial methodologies to contest the grand narrati
 ves of imperial power and violence\, and to make visible the complex lives 
 of those subjected to imperial rule. Her most recent works include Gender H
 istory: A Very Short Introduction (OUP 2024) and\, with Renisa Mawani and S
 amantha Frost\, Biocultural Empire: New Histories of Imperial Lifeworlds (B
 loomsbury 2024). She is the recipient of awards for her research from the N
 EH\, the ACLS and the Guggenheim Foundation\, and for her work as director 
 of the Humanities Research Institute from the Mellon Foundation. In 2025 sh
 e was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. Her latest edit
 ed collection\, Up Against the Archive: Experiments in Writing British Hist
 ory Otherwise\, is forthcoming from Duke University Press in 2027.
DTEND:20260409T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260408T233000Z
GEO:45.480644;-122.627381
LOCATION:Psychology\, 105
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Post/Imperial Longing: Cornelia Sorabji in Victorian Oxford
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52083564086252
URL:https://events.reed.edu/event/postimperial-longing-cornelia-sorabji-in-
 victorian-oxford
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Reed College": "https://events.reed.edu/event/decoding-scriptures-humanities-research-unbound"}
X-SOURCE-ID:reed_college
X-SOURCE:Reed College
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Join Dr. Richard Newton as he leads us in an interactive evenin
 g considering a fascinating complex in human development: scriptures. Newto
 n will guide us on an odyssey from papyri to the printing press\, from Bibl
 es to scrapbooks\, and algorithms to artificial intelligence.  Come learn a
 bout those cultural texts that people read and that also seem to read them 
 back.\n\nDr. Richard Newton is Associate Professor and Undergraduate Direct
 or in the Department of Religious Studies at the University of Alabama. New
 ton explores how people create “scriptures” and their role in identity form
 ation and cultural boundaries. Known for transdisciplinary research\, digit
 al methods\, and creative public engagement\, Newton presents religion as a
  provocative opportunity to consider how human beings work.
DTEND:20260409T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260312T160904Z
DTSTART:20260408T234500Z
GEO:45.480972;-122.630792
LOCATION:Eliot Hall\, 314
