DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260422T153000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260422T170000
LOCATION:Beth Miller Lounge (2nd Floor Fowler)
SUMMARY:First Generation Table TAlks
DESCRIPTION:Hello First-Generation* Community and those interested!  We a
 re excited to have you join us for our monthly First-Gen Table Talks!Purp
 ose of Event:Be in community and network with other First-Generation stud
 ents\, staff\, and faculty    Gain navigational skills by asking 'adultin
 g 101' questions (examples could include: how to buy a car\, what is a cr
 edit score\, how to make the most of college\, what am I doing here?! The
 re is no such thing as a silly question!)    Enjoy a free community meal 
    Spring 2026 First-Gen Table Talk:          Wednesday\, April 22nd\, 20
 26\, from 3:30-5 pm\, Beth Miller Lounge (2nd Floor of Fowler)        Spe
 cial Guest: TBD          Table Talk Logistics:RSVP here (https://forms.gl
 e/RfKheHghnzFEjomp9) to let us know if you plan to attend! We'll send you
  an email reminder leading up to our event!          Food will be provide
 d - supplies will be limited\, so come when you can! Please feel free to 
 bring your own lunch as well.          These events are meant to be infor
 mal\; please feel free to come/go as your schedule allows. No need to sta
 y the entire time.              Our table talk series is hosted by First-
 Gen staff member Kamariah Hammonds (IME\, Assistant Director)      Questi
 ons? Email us at IME (multicultural@lclark.edu).  *Like any identity\, id
 entifying a clear definition is always challenging\, as each individual i
 s complex and unique. Defining a First-Generation College Student is no d
 ifferent and can be complicated. IME welcomes any student who believes th
 ey would benefit from our First-Generation Programs. We encourage you to 
 reach out to IME if you have questions about defining who is First-Genera
 tion and/or if you would like to share more about your experience!
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<div>  Hello First-Generation* Community and
  those interested!</div><div></div><div>  We are excited to have you join
  us for our monthly First-Gen Table Talks!</div><div></div><div><strong>P
 urpose of Event:</strong></div><div><ul><li>Be in community and network w
 ith other First-Generation students\, staff\, and faculty    </li><li>Gai
 n navigational skills by asking 'adulting 101' questions (examples could 
 include: how to buy a car\, what is a credit score\, how to make the most
  of college\, what am I doing here?! There is no such thing as a silly qu
 estion!)    </li><li>Enjoy a free community meal    </li></ul></div><div>
 <div><strong>Spring 2026 First-Gen Table Talk:</strong></div><div><ul><li
 ><p>          Wednesday\, April 22nd\, 2026\, from 3:30-5 pm\, Beth Mille
 r Lounge (2nd Floor of Fowler)        </p><ul><li>Special Guest: TBD     
      </li></ul></li></ul><div><div><strong>Table Talk Logistics:</strong>
 </div><div><ul><li><a href="https://forms.gle/RfKheHghnzFEjomp9" target="
 _blank" rel="noopener">RSVP here</a> to let us know if you plan to attend
 ! We'll send you an email reminder leading up to our event!          </li
 ><li>Food will be provided - supplies will be limited\, so come when you 
 can! Please feel free to bring your own lunch as well.          </li><li>
 These events are meant to be informal\; please feel free to come/go as yo
 ur schedule allows. No need to stay the entire time.          </li></ul><
 /div></div></div><div>    Our table talk series is hosted by First-Gen st
 aff member Kamariah Hammonds (IME\, Assistant Director)  </div><div></div
 ><div>    Questions? Email us at IME (multicultural@lclark.edu).  </div><
 /div><div></div><div><i>*Like any identity\, identifying a clear definiti
 on is always challenging\, as each individual is complex and unique. Defi
 ning a First-Generation College Student is no different and can be compli
 cated. IME welcomes any student who believes they would benefit from our 
 First-Generation Programs. We encourage you to reach out to IME if you ha
 ve questions about defining who is First-Generation and/or if you would l
 ike to share more about your experience!</i></div>
