DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T100000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Trauma-Informed Clinical Supervision (Online)
DESCRIPTION:The field of counseling and therapy stands at a crossroads: w
 e must confront societal dysfunction and decide whether to challenge it o
 r perpetuate it.  As supervisors\, our role is to support clinicians' abi
 lity to acknowledge and utilize our privilege and power to better serve c
 lients and communities. Once we look beyond pathologizing models\, we can
  acknowledge the roles that society and other systems play in oppressing 
 or empowering our clients.  Clinicians and supervisors can promote equity
  by applying integrated\, trauma-informed practices and care models that 
 consider mental health\, neurodivergence\, socioeconomic status and racia
 l factors\, while incorporating present-oriented\, strengths-based approa
 ches.&#160\;  This training equips supervisors with practical skills and 
 clinical tools for trauma-informed supervision that can be used with both
  their supervisees and the clients they serve.During this workshop partic
 ipants will:      Learn integrative approaches to supervision that emphas
 ize the need for holistic self-awareness as a clinician          Explore 
 the ethics of authenticity and therapeutic transparency to build trauma-i
 nformed trust\, and encourage growth through interpersonal neurobiologica
 l safety          Examine factors that create obstacles to trauma-informe
 d supervision and develop strategies to reduce reactivity that may be pas
 sed on to clients    Details &amp\; RegistrationDate and Time: Friday\, M
 ay 1\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-1 p.m. PST\, OnlinePresenter:&#160\;Julianna Vermeys
 \, LPCCost and Credits: $105\, includes 4 CEUs. GSEC Alumni\, Adjuncts\, 
 and Clinical Mental Health Supervisors save 20%.&#160\;Register Online (h
 ttps://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002IrRJ)Registration ends
  after Tuesday\, April 28thAccessibility: We are committed to making our 
 events accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, please l
 et us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.ed
 u (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#
 x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are for current students only 
 and do not include continuing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the Instru
 ctorJulianna Vermeys\, LPC has been practicing integrative somatic psycho
 therapy since 2006. She is dedicated to offering trauma-informed\, holist
 ic therapy that addresses systemic\, environmental and relational impacts
  through one's lifespan. Julianna offers equitable\, existential and soma
 tic oriented supervision clinical supervision as an approved supervisor f
 or the OBLPCT. She is inspired by family/relationship dynamics\, attachme
 nt\, human development\, trauma-informed healing and wellness\, and clien
 t-centered therapy rooted in compassion and unconditional positive regard
 . She has specialized training in trauma-informed counseling\, mindfulnes
 s\, and body-based therapies. Julianna is registered with Yoga Alliance a
 s RYT 500-hr and is excited by the collective considerations of how we ca
 n embrace ancient practices from other cultures with ethical\, conscious 
 care. She teaches graduate classes as an adjunct faculty member at the Le
 wis &amp\; Clark Graduate School in the Counseling Program\, and offers t
 rainings for clinicians in trauma informed embodiment practices to inform
  ethical clinical work and integrated somatic psychotherapy.New workshops
  and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on pro
 fessional development related to your specific interests\, sign up for ou
 r mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
