  counseling and therapy stands at a crossroads: we must confront societal
  dysfunction and decide whether to challenge it or perpetuate it.</p><p s
 tyle="line-height: 1.5\;">  As supervisors\, our role is to support clini
 cians' ability to acknowledge and utilize our privilege and power to bett
 er serve clients and communities. Once we look beyond pathologizing model
 s\, we can acknowledge the roles that society and other systems play in o
 ppressing or empowering our clients.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  C
 linicians and supervisors can promote equity by applying integrated\, tra
 uma-informed practices and care models that consider mental health\, neur
 odivergence\, socioeconomic status and racial factors\, while incorporati
 ng present-oriented\, strengths-based approaches.&#160\;</p><p style="lin
 e-height: 1.5\;">  This training equips supervisors with practical skills
  and clinical tools for trauma-informed supervision that can be used with
  both their supervisees and the clients they serve.</p><h4 style="line-he
 ight: 1.5\;"><strong>During this workshop participants will:</strong></h4
