SUMMARY:Trans Form: Grounding into Trans History\, Liberation\, and Hope 
 (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:At TransActive (https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continui
 ng_education/transactive/) we are working to strengthen the systems that 
 surround trans and gender diverse youth. This workshop will help particip
 ants to build a clear understanding of the current political climate we a
 re experiencing\, and discuss how we can leverage effective communication
 \, liberatory practices\, and community engagement to support trans lives
  in this moment.During the workshop participants will:Reflect on the hist
 ory of anti-trans legislation  Take a clear look at the past 10 years of 
 laws affecting transgender people\, both across the United States and her
 e in Oregon\, to better understand the broader context shaping people's l
 ives today.Practice effective communication  Learn strategies for talking
  about these topics with clients and families in ways that are clear\, re
 spectful\, and appropriate for different ages.Explore actionable liberato
 ry practices  Discuss what liberation looks like in action\, bringing tog
 ether social change research with examples of practice established by tra
 nsgender leaders.Map our communities  Create maps of our own communities 
 and explore opportunities to practice community\, leverage change\, and s
 trengthen connections with our people and our values.Following the worksh
 op\, participants will be able to:Explain the social-political processes 
 that have resulted in increased political targeting of transgender and ge
 nder nonconforming communities  Speak to the local political landscape an
 d current protections and challenges in Oregon for transgender communitie
 s  Identify and explain personal hope practice  Understand one to three l
 everage points for enacting change can be utilized to support transgender
  communities in the current political climate    This training is for any
 one supporting trans and gender-diverse youth—including educators\, the
 rapists\, health care providers\, organizers\, parents\, and caregivers
 and is designed to deepen understanding of our current moment while embe
 dding liberatory\, trans-centered practices into daily life and work.  Th
 is workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Competence Continuing Education 
 requirement. Click here for more information (http://www.oregon.gov/oblpc
 t/Pages/CCCE.aspx)Event DetailsDate and Time: Saturday\, May 30\, 2026\, 
 9 a.m-4 p.m.Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South ChapelIn
 structors: Carson Varnum\, MEd\, and Finn Johnson&#160\;RegistrationCommu
 nity &amp\; Graduate Student Rate: $60 (no CEUs or PDUs)CEU/PDU Registrat
 ion: $140\, includes 6 CEUs or PDUs\, GSEC Alumni and Adjuncts save 20%Cu
 rrent GSEC Supervisors: $112\, includes 6 CEUs or PDUs  Limited no-cost r
 egistrations available for GSEC Faculty and Staff. Email cce@lclark.edu (
 mailto:cce@lclark.edu) to register.Register Online (https://lclark.tfafor
 ms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002P22H)Workshop registration ends May 24\, 2
 026Accessibility: We are committed to making our events accessible to all
  needs and abilities. When registering\, please let us know your access n
 eeds. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu
 )&#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x20
 19\; registrations are for current students only and do not include conti
 nuing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorsCarson Varnum\, MEd
 \, (he/him) is a community builder and educator with an expertise in sexu
 al health\, sexualities\, peer education\, and community development. Car
 son specializes in building capacity in sex educators\, creating sexualit
 y education and leadership development programming for adolescents\, and 
 developing programs that center Queer and Trans communities. Carson works
  at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School as TransActives's Head of Educatio
 n and Outreach\, where he supports transgender\, non-binary\, and other g
 ender expansive youth by strengthening the systems that surround them. He
  received his Masters of Education in Human Sexuality from Widener Univer
 sity in 2012 and is currently a PhD student in Education and Leadership a
 t Pacific University. Carson is a big fan of being on mountains\, in rive
 rs\, and with friends.&#160\;Finn Johnson (he/him) is a PhD Candidate in 
 Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies and Ethnic Studies at Oregon State
  University\, and a law student at Lewis &amp\; Clark Law School. He hold
 s an MA in Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies from Oregon State and a
  BA in Sexuality\, Gender\, and Queer Studies from Portland State Univers
 ity. Before law school\, Finn taught and developed undergraduate courses 
 in Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies at Oregon State\, focusing on q
 ueer and trans studies. He also publishes scholarship in Critical Race Th
 eory\, Critical Legal Studies\, and LGBTQIA+ STEM Studies. His doctoral r
 esearch has examined anti-transgender legislation in the U.S. since 2016.
  Beyond research\, he has extensive experience as an activist\, lobbyist\
 , and community educator in LGBTQIA+ and reproductive justice policy.New 
 workshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the late
 st on professional development related to your specific interests\, sign 
 up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
