BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lewis Clark": "https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/375747-body-politics-online"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lewis_clark
X-SOURCE:Lewis Clark
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260627T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260627T173000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Body Politics (Online)
DESCRIPTION:As clinicians\, we need to be prepared to help clients decons
 truct how their bodies have been storied.  This includes raising awarenes
 s of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational power dyna
 mics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the everyday 
 realities of our lives.  This course explores how we evaluate our bodies 
 through the lens of "unidentified others\," as well as the lived experien
 ce and consequences of looks\, privilege and discrimination.  Participant
 s will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the obje
 ctification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in late cap
 italist societies.  The focus of this course is to raise awareness of bod
 y politics in the clinical practice and creating opportunities for change
  through individual and relational wellbeing.  This course is part of our
  Eating Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/progra
 ms/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).Course Details &a
 mp\; RegistrationDates and Times: Saturday-Sunday\, June 27-28\, 2026\, 9
  a.m.-3:50 p.m.Instructor:&#160\;Krystal Marcinkiewicz\, MA\, LPC\, LMHCC
 urrent Students and Certificate Candidates: CECP 837-1\, 1 semester hour 
 of Graduate Continuing Education credit\, $385.&#160\;Individual Class: W
 e welcome students seeking to take individual courses within the certific
 ate program. Admission to the program is required. Click here for more in
 formation (https://www.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/certifica
 tes/eating_disorders/#Admission)Register Online (https://lclark.tfaforms.
 net/4735425)We are committed to making our events accessible to all needs
  and abilities. If you have a disability that may impact your academic pe
 rformance\, you may request accommodations by meeting with the Office of 
 Student Accessibility staff and submitting documentation on the Office of
  Student Accessibility website (/offices/student-accessibility/). Please 
 be aware that the process for evaluation and implementation of accommodat
 ions could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in touch with the OSA as soon as
  possible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:access@lclark.edu) with any ad
 ditional questions or concerns.About the Instructor Krystal Marcinkiewicz
 \, MA\, LPC\, LMHC is a Licensed Professional Counselor and Clinical Supe
 rvisor\, having earned her Masters Degree in Professional Mental Health C
 ounseling from Lewis &amp\; Clark College in 2018. Drawing from an integr
 ative feminist approach\, her work is grounded in person-centered values\
 , emphasizing authentic connection\, and collaborative engagement. Her pr
 imary clinical focus is supporting clients in navigating identity develop
 ment\, body politics\, neurodivergence\, emotional codependency\, highly 
 sensitive personalities and other complex emotional experiences.  In addi
 tion to clinical work\, Krystal is also passionate in training and mentor
 ing emerging counselors. She is an adjunct professor\, teaching a wide va
 riety of graduate counseling courses with an underlying emphasis on couns
 elor identity development\, reflective practice\, and cultivating profess
 ional resilience.  In both the classroom\, and her clinical work\, Krysta
 l is committed to creating affirming spaces that honor intersectional ide
 ntities and lived experience.New workshops and trainings are added to our
  calendar regularly. For the latest on professional development related t
 o your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark
 .tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As clinician
 s\, we need to be prepared to help clients deconstruct how their bodies h
 ave been storied.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This includes raisin
 g awareness of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational 
 power dynamics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the
  everyday realities of our lives.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This
  course explores how we evaluate our bodies through the lens of "unidenti
 fied others\," as well as the lived experience and consequences of looks\
 , privilege and discrimination.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Partic
 ipants will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the
  objectification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in lat
 e capitalist societies.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  The focus of t
 his course is to raise awareness of body politics in the clinical practic
 e and creating opportunities for change through individual and relational
  wellbeing.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This course is part of our
  <a href="https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/certi
 ficates/eating_disorders/">Eating Disorders Certificate Program</a>.</p><
