X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Lewis Clark": "https://www.lclark.edu/calendars/events/event/375748-body-politics-online"}
X-SOURCE-ID:lewis_clark
X-SOURCE:Lewis Clark
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260711T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260711T173000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Body Politics (Online)
DESCRIPTION:As clinicians\, we need to be prepared to help clients decons
 truct how their bodies have been storied.  This includes raising awarenes
 s of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational power dyna
 mics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the everyday 
 realities of our lives.  This course explores how we evaluate our bodies 
 through the lens of "unidentified others\," as well as the lived experien
 ce and consequences of looks\, privilege and discrimination.  Participant
 s will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the obje
 ctification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in late cap
 italist societies.  The focus of this course is to raise awareness of bod
 y politics in the clinical practice and creating opportunities for change
  through individual and relational wellbeing.  This course is part of our
  Eating Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/progra
 ms/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).Course Details &a
 mp\; RegistrationDates and Times: Saturday &amp\; Sunday\, July 11 &amp\;
  12\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m.Instructor: Krystal Marcinkiewicz\, MA\, LPC
 \, LMHCCurrent Students and Certificate Candidates: CECP 837-2\, 1 semest
 er hour of Graduate Continuing Education credit\, $385.&#160\;Individual 
 Class: We welcome students seeking to take individual courses within the 
 certificate program. Admission to the program is required. Click here for
  more information (https://www.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/c
 ertificates/eating_disorders/#Admission)Register Online (https://lclark.t
 faforms.net/4735425)We are committed to making our events accessible to a
 ll needs and abilities. If you have a disability that may impact your aca
 demic performance\, you may request accommodations by meeting with the Of
 fice of Student Accessibility staff and submitting documentation on the O
 ffice of Student Accessibility website (/offices/student-accessibility/).
  Please be aware that the process for evaluation and implementation of ac
 commodations could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in touch with the OSA as
  soon as possible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:access@lclark.edu) wit
 h any additional questions or concerns.About the Instructor Krystal Marci
 nkiewicz\, MA\, LPC\, LMHC is a Licensed Professional Counselor and Clini
 cal Supervisor\, having earned her Masters Degree in Professional Mental 
 Health Counseling from Lewis &amp\; Clark College in 2018. Drawing from a
 n integrative feminist approach\, her work is grounded in person-centered
  values\, emphasizing authentic connection\, and collaborative engagement
 . Her primary clinical focus is supporting clients in navigating identity
  development\, body politics\, neurodivergence\, emotional codependency\,
  highly sensitive personalities and other complex emotional experiences. 
  In addition to clinical work\, Krystal is also passionate in training an
 d mentoring emerging counselors. She is an adjunct professor\, teaching a
  wide variety of graduate counseling courses with an underlying emphasis 
 on counselor identity development\, reflective practice\, and cultivating
  professional resilience.  In both the classroom\, and her clinical work\
 , Krystal is committed to creating affirming spaces that honor intersecti
 onal identities and lived experience.New workshops and trainings are adde
 d to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professional development r
 elated to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https:
 //lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
